@model dynamic
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Republic Act No. 9482 - Anti-Rabies Act of 2007";
}

<div class="container my-5">
    <div class="card shadow-lg border-0">
        <div class="card-body">
            <h1 class="text-center mb-4">@ViewData["Title"]</h1>
            <p class="lead text-center mb-5">
                The Anti-Rabies Act of 2007 (Republic Act No. 9482) aims to strengthen the government's campaign to eliminate rabies in the country through prevention, control, and eradication programs. This act represents a comprehensive approach to addressing rabies as a significant public health concern, emphasizing the importance of responsible pet ownership and community involvement.
            </p>

            <h2 class="mt-4">Key Provisions</h2>
            <ul class="list-group mb-4">
                <li class="list-group-item">Mandatory registration of pet dogs and cats with local government units.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Requirement of anti-rabies vaccinations for pets, enforced annually.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Penalties for owners of pets involved in rabies incidents, including fines and potential imprisonment.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Public education campaigns on rabies prevention and the importance of vaccination.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Support for rabies research and development to enhance prevention and treatment strategies.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Objectives</h2>
            <p>
                The primary objectives of the Anti-Rabies Act include:
            </p>
            <ul class="list-group mb-4">
                <li class="list-group-item">Reducing the incidence of rabies through vaccination programs in urban and rural areas.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Protecting public health by controlling rabies transmission through stray animal management.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Ensuring proper care and control of domestic animals to prevent rabies spread.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Enhancing community awareness and participation in rabies prevention initiatives.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Importance of Compliance</h2>
            <p>
                Compliance with the Anti-Rabies Act is crucial for safeguarding public health and preventing rabies outbreaks. Pet owners play a vital role in this initiative, ensuring that their pets are vaccinated and registered. Local government units are tasked with monitoring compliance and conducting public awareness campaigns to educate communities on the risks associated with rabies.
            </p>

            <h2>Penalties for Non-Compliance</h2>
            <p>
                The Anti-Rabies Act imposes strict penalties on pet owners who fail to comply with the regulations. These penalties include:
            </p>
            <ul class="list-group mb-4">
                <li class="list-group-item">Fines ranging from PHP 1,000 to PHP 5,000 for failing to register pets or for not vaccinating them against rabies.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Imprisonment of up to 6 months for repeat offenders or for cases involving serious incidents of rabies.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Liability for damages or injuries caused by pets that are not properly vaccinated or registered.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Responsibilities of Pet Owners</h2>
            <p>
                Pet owners have several responsibilities under the Anti-Rabies Act, including:
            </p>
            <ul class="list-group mb-4">
                <li class="list-group-item">Ensuring their pets are vaccinated against rabies annually.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Registering their pets with the local government unit.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Keeping their pets under control to prevent them from becoming strays.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Reporting any suspected rabies cases to local authorities.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Responsibilities of Barangay Officials</h2>
            <p>
                Barangay officials also have crucial responsibilities in enforcing the Anti-Rabies Act, which include:
            </p>
            <ul class="list-group mb-4">
                <li class="list-group-item">Conducting regular vaccination drives and pet registration campaigns.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Monitoring compliance with pet registration and vaccination laws.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Managing stray animal populations through humane methods, including capture and vaccination.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item">Educating the community about rabies prevention and responsible pet ownership.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>References</h2>
            <div class="reference mb-4">
                For more details, you can refer to the full text of the law at <a href="https://paws.org.ph/downloads/ra9482_anti_rabies_act_of_2007.pdf" target="_blank">Official Gazette</a>.
            </div>

            <p class="note">
                Note: It is essential for all pet owners to stay informed about their responsibilities under this act to contribute effectively to the elimination of rabies in the country.
            </p>

            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>
            <div class="faq mb-4">
                <h3>1. What is the purpose of the Anti-Rabies Act?</h3>
                <p>The Anti-Rabies Act aims to strengthen the government's efforts to eliminate rabies through prevention, control, and education programs.</p>

                <h3>2. Who is responsible for vaccinating pets?</h3>
                <p>Pet owners are responsible for ensuring their pets are vaccinated against rabies annually.</p>

                <h3>3. What are the penalties for not complying with the Anti-Rabies Act?</h3>
                <p>Penalties include fines ranging from PHP 1,000 to PHP 5,000 and imprisonment of up to 6 months for repeat offenders.</p>

                <h3>4. How can I report a suspected rabies case?</h3>
                <p>Pet owners should report any suspected rabies cases to their local government unit or barangay officials.</p>

                <h3>5. What should I do if I find a stray animal?</h3>
                <p>Report the stray animal to local authorities who can manage it appropriately and ensure it receives vaccinations.</p>

                <h3>6. How often do pets need to be vaccinated against rabies?</h3>
                <p>Pets must be vaccinated against rabies at least once a year, but owners should consult with their veterinarians for specific vaccination schedules.</p>

                <h3>7. Are there exemptions to the vaccination requirement?</h3>
                <p>Exemptions may be granted for certain medical conditions; however, pet owners must present a veterinarian's certification to the local government unit.</p>

                <h3>8. Can I adopt a pet without following the Anti-Rabies Act?</h3>
                <p>No, all adopted pets must be registered and vaccinated according to the Anti-Rabies Act to ensure public safety.</p>

                <h3>9. What should I do if my pet bites someone?</h3>
                <p>If your pet bites someone, you should report the incident to local authorities and ensure that your pet is properly examined and vaccinated.</p>

                <h3>10. Where can I find vaccination clinics for my pets?</h3>
                <p>Local government units often conduct vaccination drives, and you can also contact veterinary clinics for regular vaccination services.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

